Author Name: **David Banas** (@capn-freako)
Original Redmine Message: 2879 from https://www.veripool.org



---

Let's say I have the following Verilog code:

```
module myMod (
  input  logic clk, x, y,
  output logic z
);

/* verilator no_inline_module */

always @(posedge clk)
  z <= x ^ y;

endmodule

module top (
  {I/O defs}
);

myMod blk1(...);
...

endmodule

```

Upon _Verilation_ I find that I have a file: @top_myMod.h@.<br>
And that file defines a class: @Vtop_myMod@.<br>
That class defines a public function: @_sequent__TOP__top__DOT__myMod__2@, which I assume is the C++ implementation of the functionality defined in the @always@ block of my @myMod@ module.<br>
Now, here's the kicker: the calling signature of that function does _not_ match the I/O signature of my @myMod@ module!<br>
Instead, it looks like this:

```
void _sequent__TOP__top__DOT__myMod__2(Vtop__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp);

```

Why?

